# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bruce-alberts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bruce-alberts/a-e-walsby] He was a researcher in the fields of Algae, Cyanobacteria, lake ecology, gas vesicles and genetics, covering the European lakes and Baltic Sea.
[src:bruce-alberts/a-e-walsby] He is noted for his discovery of *Haloquadratum walsbyi* in brine ponds on the Sinai Peninsula in 1980.
[src:bruce-alberts/a-e-walsby] He was elected Fellow of the Royal Society on 11 March 1993.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] White was born in Cleveland, Ohio, to Morris and Lena White.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] His siblings were Essie and Julius ("Jay").
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] When he was about one year old, his family moved to Lafayette, Colorado, and then later to Denver.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] White earned his bachelor's and master's degrees at the University of Colorado and a Ph.D. degree in Physiological Chemistry at the University of Michigan in the laboratory of Howard B.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] This was followed by a postdoctoral fellowship at the Yale School of Medicine with Hubert Bradford Vickery at the Connecticut Agricultural Experiment Station.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] After completing his fellowship, White joined the faculty in the Department of Physiological Chemistry at Yale, where he initially studied the amino acid composition of proteins and metabolism of sulfur-containing amino acids.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] White's research gradually moved to nutritional and growth studies in animals and investigations of the protein hormones of the pituitary gland, especially involving proteins containing sulfur.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] Beach, White proved that the amino acid methionine could be metabolized to cysteine by showing that rats could grow on a diet containing proteins that were devoid of cysteine, as long as they contained methionine.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] In 1937 White reported the isolation of bovine prolactin, the first of the pituitary hormones to be obtained in pure form, and in 1943 the isolation of porcine adrenocorticotropic hormone.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] These discoveries opened the field of biochemistry to the study of pituitary hormones and the experimental finding that administration of adrenocorticotropic hormone caused involution of lymphoid tissues.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] White eventually became acting chairman of the Department of Physiological Chemistry at Yale.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] In 1951 he became professor and chairman of the Department of Physiological Chemistry at the University of California School of Medicine in Los Angeles.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] In 1953 he moved back east to become the first faculty member, professor, the inaugural chairman of the Department of Biochemistry, and an associate dean at the newly founded Albert Einstein College of Medicine in the Bronx, New York.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] In 1954, White, along with Philip Handler and Emil L.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] Smith, published a landmark textbook, *Principles of Biochemistry*.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] Until that time, there was no standard textbook in the field.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] It was used extensively at the undergraduate and graduate level and went through six editions, the last being published in 1978.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] White retired from his appointment at Einstein in 1972 to become a consultant to Syntex Laboratories and the Stanford University School of Medicine.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] White was married to his wife Edna for more than 40 years.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] He died unexpectedly on February 14, 1980, in Santa Barbara, California, where he had gone that day from his home in Palo Alto to deliver a lecture at the University of California.
[src:bruce-alberts/abraham-white] Several awards in the field of biochemistry have been named for White, including at Oakland University in Michigan, Wayne State University, George Washington University School of Medicine and the Gladstone Institutes.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Ahmed Hassan Zewail was born on February 26, 1946, in Damanhur, Egypt, and was raised in Desouk.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] He received bachelor's and master's degrees in chemistry from Alexandria University before moving to the United States to complete his PhD at the University of Pennsylvania under the supervision of Robin M.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] After completing his PhD, Zewail did postdoctoral research at the University of California, Berkeley, supervised by Charles B.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Following this, he was awarded a faculty appointment at the California Institute of Technology in 1976, and eventually became the first Linus Pauling Chair in Chemical Physics there.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] He became a naturalized citizen of the United States on March 5, 1982.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Zewail was the director of the Physical Biology Center for Ultrafast Science and Technology at the California Institute of Technology.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Zewail's key work was a pioneer of femtochemistry—i.e. the study of chemical reactions on a femtosecond timescale.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Using a rapid ultrafast laser technique (consisting of ultrashort laser flashes), the technique allows the description of reactions on very short time scales – short enough to analyse transition states in selected chemical reactions.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Zewail became known as the "father of femtochemistry".
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] He also made critical contributions in ultrafast electron diffraction, which uses short electron pulses rather than light pulses to study chemical reaction dynamics.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] When asked about rumors that he might contest the 2012 Egyptian presidential election, Ahmed Zewail said: "I am a frank man...
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] During the 2011 Egyptian protests he announced his return to the country.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Zewail said that he would join a committee for constitutional reform alongside Ayman Nour, Mubarak's rival at the 2005 presidential elections and a leading lawyer.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Zewail was later mentioned as a respected figure working as an intermediary between the military regime ruling after Mubarak's resignation, and revolutionary youth groups such as the April 6 Youth Movement and young supporters of Mohamed ElBaradei.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] He played a critical role during this time as described by Egyptian Media.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Zewail's work brought him international attention, receiving awards and honors throughout most of his career for his work in chemistry and physics.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] In 1999, Zewail became the first Egyptian to receive a science Nobel Prize when he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Zewail gave his Nobel Lecture on "Femtochemistry: Atomic-Scale Dynamics of the Chemical Bond Using Ultrafast Lasers".
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] In 1999, he received Egypt's highest state honour, the Grand Collar of the Nile.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Other notable awards include the Alexander von Humboldt Senior Scientist Award (1983), the King Faisal International Prize (1989), the Wolf Prize in Chemistry (1993), the Earle K.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Broida Prize (1995), the Peter Debye Award (1996), the Tolman Award (1997), the Robert A.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Welch Award (1997), the Linus Pauling Medal (1997), the Franklin Medal (1998) and the Golden Plate Award of the American Academy of Achievement (2000).
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] In 1982 he was named as a Fellow of the American Physical Society.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Zewail became a member of the National Academy of Sciences in 1989, the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1993, and the American Philosophical Society in 1998.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Zewail was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Society (ForMemRS) in 2001.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] He was also elected as a Fellow of the African Academy of Sciences in 2001.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Zewail was made a Foreign Member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] In 2005, the Ahmed Zewail Award for Ultrafast Science and Technology was established by the American Chemical Society and the Newport Corporation in his honor.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] In 2010 the journal Chemical Physics Letters established the Ahmed Zewail Prize in Molecular Sciences.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] In May 2010, Zewail gave the commencement address at Southwestern University.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] The Zewail City of Science and Technology, established in 2000 and revived in 2011, is named in his honour.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Alexandria University, Egypt (1999); D.Sc.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Zewail and his first wife, Mervat, were married in 1967, just before leaving Egypt to attend the University of Pennsylvania for his PhD.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] He had two daughters with Mervat, Maha and Amani.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Mervat and Ahmed however, separated in 1979.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Zewail married Dema Faham, a Syrian, in 1989.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Zewail and Faham had two sons, Nabeel and Hani.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Zewail died aged 70 on the morning of August 2, 2016.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] He was recovering from cancer, however, the exact cause of his death is unknown.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Zewail returned to Egypt, but only his body was received at Cairo Airport.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] A military funeral was held for Zewail on August 7, 2016, at the El-Mosheer Tantawy mosque in Cairo, Egypt.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] Those attending included President Abdel Fattah el-Sisi, Prime Minister Sherif Ismail, al-Azhar Grand Imam Ahmed el-Tayeb, Defence Minister Sedki Sobhi, former President Adly Mansour, former Prime Minister Ibrahim Mahlab and heart surgeon Magdi Yacoub.
[src:bruce-alberts/ahmed-zewail] The funeral prayers were led by Ali Gomaa, former Grand Mufti of Egypt.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] He was born in Crewe, England, to Jane and Harold Astbury.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] His mother worked in a bakery and his father was an engineer for the Co-op Dairy.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] He went to Nantwich and Acton Grammar School.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] Although he was a good cricketer and footballer - he played for Crewe Schoolboys along with Chelsea and England player Frank Blunstone - his parents discouraged a career in football.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] In 1953, he joined the University of Liverpool, gaining a first-class honours degree in 1956 followed by a PhD in 1959 under Alec Merrison and Hugh Muirhead.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] He won a Leverhulme Research Fellowship to work on Liverpool's 380 MeV, 1.83m (72 inch) synchrocyclotron, the world's second-largest at the time.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] The team's work confirmed parity violation in muon capture.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] He joined Kenneth Crowe's group at Berkeley in 1961, using their 4.67m (184 inch) synchrocyclotron and working on a bent-crystal spectrometer for more precise particle mass measurement.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] In 1963, he joined the inchoative Rutherford Appleton Laboratory (RAL) structures, with their 7GeV Nimrod proton synchrotron and eventually became the RAL's Chief Principal Scientific Officer.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] There, he and others confirmed charge-parity violation in neutral kaon decay.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] In 1964, the RAL began a two-decade collaboration with Peter Kalmus's group at Queen Mary University of London (QMUL), as well as with groups from Harwell and the University of Bergen amongst others.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] Experiments were carried out on various weak and strong interactions in the UK and low-energy antiproton-proton experiments at CERN.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] In 1974, he became the chair of the Nimrod coordinating team, in 1975, the chair of the CERN Electronic Experiments Committee and in 1976 he joined the evaluation committee of Canada's national particle accelerator, TRIUMF.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] In 1977, the RAL and QMUL groups, along with John Dowell's group at the University of Birmingham and Muirhead - Astbury's former tutor at Liverpool - joined Carlo Rubbia in the UA1 collaboration at CERN.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] The Super Proton Synchrotron which had been designed by John Adam was converted under Rubbia's guidance to a collider, the Super Proton–Antiproton Synchrotron.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] The British contingent created and operated the large hadron calorimeter.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] Rubbia and Astbury became joint spokespeople for the UA1 project.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] Later, the existence of the W and Z particles was confirmed, gaining Rubbia and Simon van der Meer the 1984 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] Astbury became a professor at the University of Victoria, receiving significant funding for his research.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] In 1986, he became a member of the Canadian Natural Sciences and Engineering Research Council (NSERC) grant selection committee and, in 1991, director of Canada's Institute of Particle Physics (IPP).
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] He used his skills when becoming director of TRIUMF in 1994 to further direct Canadian involvement in CERN with contributions to the Large Hadron Collider ATLAS experiment, in addition to the continuing OPAL experiment of the Large Electron–Positron Collider.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] He served as president of the International Union of Pure and Applied Physics (IUPAP) from 2005 to 2008.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] He organised new memberships, instigated the IUPAP Young Scientist Medal and Prize and promoted the increased participation of women in the commissions and executive council.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-astbury] He died in 2014, survived by his wife, Kathleen (née Stratmeyer), and daughters Elizabeth and Gillian.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] Baddeley was born in Leeds, Yorkshire on 23 March 1934.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] He lived there with his parents, Donald and Nellie Baddeley, until leaving for university.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] He decided to study psychology and was originally interested in psychoanalysis.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] Later he changed his focus to evidence-based psychology.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] In 1956, Baddeley went to the United States of America to continue his studies.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] After spending a year in America, he returned home.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] He then went to Cambridge, where he met and married Hilary Ann White.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] Baddeley has taught and conducted research at University of Sussex, University of Stirling, MRC Applied Psychology Unit, Churchill College, University of Cambridge, and University of Bristol.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] He is currently a professor of psychology at the University of York.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] Baddeley attended the University College London from 1953 to 1956.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] He then obtained an MA from Princeton University's Department of Psychology in 1957.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] He earned a PhD from University of Cambridge in 1962.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] He has been awarded Honorary Doctorates by University of Essex in 1999, Plymouth University in 2000, and University of Bristol in 2019.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] In 1974, working with Graham Hitch, Baddeley developed an influential model of working memory called Baddeley's model of working memory, which argues for the existence of multiple short-term memory stores and a separate interacting system for manipulating the content of these stores.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] There are three components of this model: the phonological loop, the central executive, and the visuospatial sketch pad.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] In 2000, Baddeley suggested adding a fourth component to his memory model called the episodic buffer.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] The model accounts for much of the empirical data on short-term retention and manipulation of information.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] His landmark study in 1975 on the capacity of short-term memory showed that people remembered more short words than long words in a recall test.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] This was called the word length effect and it demonstrated that pronunciation time rather than number of items determines the capacity of verbal short-term memory.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] This study also found that when participants repeated an irrelevant sound while reading the words, the word length effect does not happen.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] Working with Barbara Wilson, Baddeley also did several important studies on amnesia and memory.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] They studied patients with temporal lobe damage that caused memory problems.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] Results of such studies provide evidence that short-term and long-term memory are not one system.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] The amnesia patients had normal short-term memory but impaired long-term memory.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] Baddeley has also done research studies using divers and various underwater conditions.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] He studied the effects of depth and pressure on dexterity, the impact of temperature on response time, and context-dependent memory on land and underwater.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] Baddeley was the director of the Cognition and Brain Sciences Unit, a branch of the UK Medical Research Council, based in Cambridge, from 1974 - 1997.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] He was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society in 1993 and in 1996, was elected a Foreign Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] In 2001, Baddeley received the American Psychological Association (APA) Award for Distinguished Scientific Contributions.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] Baddeley was given the Lifetime Achievement Award by the British Psychological Society in 2012.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] He also received the Major Advancement in Psychological Science Prize from the International Union of Psychological Science in 2016.
[src:bruce-alberts/alan-baddeley] Baddeley was involved in the design of United Kingdom postcodes, and was one of the founders of the European Society for Cognitive Psychology.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] Alanna Schepartz was born on January 9, 1962, in New York City and was raised in Rego Park, Queens.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] She graduated from Forest Hills High School in 1978 at the age of 16.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] She then earned a B.S. degree in chemistry from the State University of New York, Albany and a PhD degree in Organic Chemistry from Columbia University, where she worked under the supervision of Ronald Breslow.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] Following an N.I.H. postdoctoral fellowship with Peter Dervan at the California Institute of Technology, she joined the faculty at Yale University in July 1988.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] Schepartz joined the faculty at Yale University in July 1988.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] She was promoted to associate professor in 1992, to Full Professor with tenure in 1995, and was named the Milton Harris, '29 PhD Professor of Chemistry in 2000.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] In 2001, she was named a professor in the Department of Molecular, Cellular, and Developmental Biology.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] From 2002 to 2007, she held a Howard Hughes Medical Institute Professorship.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] In 2017, she was named a Sterling Professor, Yale's highest faculty honor.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] Schepartz is the first woman to be granted tenure in Yale's Department of Chemistry, and the first female Full Professor in any physical sciences department at Yale.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] Schepartz works in the field known as chemical biology.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] Her laboratory is well known for the creative application of chemical principles to understand and control biological recognition and function.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] The development of β-peptide bundles was cited by *Chemical and Engineering News*, a weekly news magazine of the chemical world, as one of 2007's “most important research advances”.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] In 2017, Schepartz was appointed by Yale as Sterling Professor of Chemistry.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] In 2019, she joined UC Berkeley College of Chemistry.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] Schepartz is the Principal Investigator at the Schepartz Laboratory of Chemical Biology.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] According to the Schepartz Laboratory Website, the laboratory "develops chemical tools to study and manipulate protein–protein and protein–DNA interactions inside the cell.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] Our approach centers on the design of molecules that nature did not synthesize—miniature proteins, β-peptide foldamers, polyproline hairpins, and proto-fluorescent ligands—and the use of these molecules to answer biological questions that would otherwise be nearly impossible to address.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] In 1990, Schepartz was awarded a David and Lucile Packard Foundation Fellowship.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] In 1991, Schepartz earned an Eli Lilly Biochemistry Fellowship, a Morse Faculty Fellowship from Yale, and a National Science Foundation Presidential Young Investigator Award.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] In 1993, she earned a Camille and Henry Dreyfus Teacher-Scholar Award, and in 1994 received an Alfred P.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] Cope Scholar Award in 1995 and an A.C.S.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] Eli Lilly Award in Biological Chemistry in 1997.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] In 1999, she received the Dylan Hixon ’88 Award for Teaching Excellence in the Natural Sciences, and in 2002, she was awarded the Agnes Fay Morgan Research Award.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] Westheimer Prize Medal from Harvard University.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] In 2012, she was awarded the Ronald Breslow Award for Achievement in Biomimetic Chemistry.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] Throughout her career she has also been invited to be a distinguished guest speaker and lecturer.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] In 2014, she was elected to membership in the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:bruce-alberts/alanna-schepartz] Since 2005, she had served as an associate editor of the *Journal of the American Chemical Society*, and in 2016 was appointed as editor-in-chief of *Biochemistry*.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:bruce-alberts/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Alberts was the president of the National Academy of Sciences from 1993 to 2005.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] He is known for his work in forming science public policy, and has served as United States Science Envoy to Pakistan and Indonesia.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] He has stated that "Science education should be about learning to think and solve problems like a scientist—insisting, for all citizens, that statements be evaluated using evidence and logic the way scientists evaluate statements." He is an Honorary Fellow of St Edmund's College, Cambridge.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] After graduating from New Trier High School in Winnetka, Illinois, Alberts attended Harvard College, as a pre-medicine major.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Bored by assigned laboratory "cooking classes", he petitioned to skip the physical chemistry laboratory requirement and instead was allowed to work with his tutor Jacques Fresco, in Paul M.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] The summer's research led to the publication of two successful papers on mismatch errors in the helical structures of DNA and RNA, and Alberts decided to continue on in biophysics.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] He graduated with his bachelor's degree in biochemical sciences, summa cum laude, in 1960.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Doty on "enormously ambitious" PhD thesis projects, first attempting to solve the genetic code using nearest neighbor analysis after treatment of DNA with various mutagens, and then trying to test his theoretical model for how DNA polymerase could replicate a double-helical DNA template.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] After failing his first oral examination in spring 1965, he completed his Ph.D. research in fall 1965.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] His doctorate in biophysics was finally awarded by Harvard University in 1966.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Alberts credits his initial failure with teaching him much more than his successes.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] "That was a very important learning experience for me.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] After graduating, Alberts went to the Institut de Biologie Moléculaire at the University of Geneva as a postdoctoral fellow, and worked with Richard H.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Epstein on genes involved in DNA replication of phage T4.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Epstein and his students had shown that there were at least seven different proteins needed for replication of T4 DNA.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Alberts decided to do something that no one else was doing, and developed a DNA column for the purification of proteins that bound to DNA.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] This enabled him to purify the T4 Bacteriophage Gene 32 protein, thus identifying the first single-stranded DNA binding protein – a type of protein now known to be present in all cells.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] In 1966, Alberts joined the department of biochemical sciences at Princeton University as an assistant professor.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] In 1971, he became an associate professor and in 1973 a full professor, holding the Damon Pfeiffer Professorship in life sciences from 1975 to 1976.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] At Princeton, he continued to work in the area of protein biochemistry, eventually reconstituting a DNA replication system in a test tube from seven purified proteins.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] In 1976, Alberts accepted a position as professor and vice-chair of the department of biochemistry and biophysics at the University of California, San Francisco.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Also in 1976, he and his students were able to add all seven proteins to double-stranded DNA in an appropriate magnesium concentration to make DNA.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] More years of research were spent understanding the details of the reactions involved in the 7-protein “machine” that replicated DNA.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Another important step in understanding DNA synthesis was the discovery that the leading strand DNA polymerase and lagging strand DNA polymerase were coupled.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Alberts was elected a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1978.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] From 1981 to 1985 Alberts held an American Cancer Society Research Professorship, a title granted for life as of 1980.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] From 1985 to 1990, he was chair of the department of biochemistry and biophysics at the University of California, San Francisco, and from 1990 to 1993 he again held an American Cancer Society Research Professorship.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Alberts served as the full-time President of the National Academy of Sciences for two terms, moving to Washington, D.C. from 1993 until 2005.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Alberts has long been committed to the improvement of science education, dedicating much of his time to educational projects such as City Science, a program seeking to improve science teaching in San Francisco elementary schools.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] From 2005 to 2024, he served as Board Chair for the *Strategic Education Research Partnership (SERP)*, a non-profit focused on carrying out use-inspired education research, established according to recommendations in the*2003 report from the National Academies*.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] The Bruce Alberts Award for Excellence in Science Education is given in his name by the American Society for Cell Biology to those who have made outstanding contributions in science education.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] He has served in different capacities on a number of advisory and editorial boards, including as chair of the Commission on Life Sciences, National Research Council.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Prior to his election as president of the National Academy of Sciences in 1995 he was president-elect of the American Society for Biochemistry and Molecular Biology.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] From 2007 to 2008 he served as president of the American Society for Cell Biology.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] He served as a trustee of the Carnegie Corporation of New York from 2000 to 2009, and as a trustee of the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation from 2005 to 2021.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Alberts was editor-in-chief of the American Association for the Advancement of Science's flagship publication, *Science* for five years from 2008 to 2013.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] He is one of the founding editors of the journal *Cell Biology Education*.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Since 2013, Alberts has been listed on the Advisory Council of the National Center for Science Education.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] From 2000 to 2009, Alberts was the co-chair of the InterAcademy Council, an advisory institution in Amsterdam governed by the presidents of fifteen science academies from around the world.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] This organization has since been renamed the InterAcademy Panel for Policy, and it is now located in Trieste.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Alberts has had a productive research career in the field of DNA replication and cell division.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] His textbook, *Molecular Biology of the Cell*, now in its seventh edition, is the standard cell biology textbook in most universities; the *fourth edition* is freely available from National Center for Biotechnology Information Bookshelf.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] This book and its counterpart for undergraduate students, *Essential Cell Biology,* have been translated into multiple languages.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] Alberts is a member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, the National Academy of Sciences, and the American Philosophical Society.
[src:bruce-alberts/bruce-alberts] In 2014, Alberts was awarded the National Medal of Science by President Barack Obama.
